# Embed Guide — Custom Host

Generated by `/atw.embed` on {{generatedAt}}.

Answers captured in [`.atw/state/embed-answers.md`](../state/embed-answers.md).
The values below were **inlined from `.atw/config/project.md`**.

---

Your host application is not one of the frameworks `/atw.embed` recognises
directly. The integration still reduces to three things:

1. Make `widget.js` and `widget.css` reachable from the browser.
2. Add one `<link>` and one `<script>` to every page.
3. Configure CORS on **both** your host API and the ATW backend.

---

## 1. Serve the bundle

Wherever your host serves static assets, drop the two files. Adjust the
destination to your stack — **REPLACE THIS** path:

**bash**

```bash
cp dist/widget.js <your-static-dir>/widget.js
cp dist/widget.css <your-static-dir>/widget.css
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item dist/widget.js <your-static-dir>/widget.js
Copy-Item dist/widget.css <your-static-dir>/widget.css
```

## 2. Add the tags

The launcher initialises as soon as the script loads. The `data-*`
attributes configure everything:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="<url to widget.css>" />
<script
  src="<url to widget.js>"
  defer
  data-backend-url="{{atwBackendOrigin}}"
  data-api-base-url="{{hostApiOrigin}}"
  data-auth-mode="{{authMode}}"
{{#if authTokenKey}}  data-auth-token-key="{{authTokenKey}}"
{{/if}}  data-launcher-position="bottom-right"
  data-locale="{{locale}}"
{{#if loginUrl}}  data-login-url="{{loginUrl}}"
{{/if}}></script>
```

The widget reads its tool catalogue at boot from
`{{atwBackendOrigin}}/tools` — there is no `data-allowed-tools`
attribute (FR-015).

## 3. Auth modes

- **`cookie`** — default. The widget passes `credentials: 'include'` on
  host-API calls; your host must be configured to accept the cookie
  (same-site or explicit CORS with `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials`).
- **`bearer`** — the widget reads `localStorage[data-auth-token-key]` on
  every call and attaches `Authorization: Bearer <value>`.
- **`custom`** — define `window.AtwAuthProvider` as an async function
  returning a header map; the widget will call it for every host-API
  request.

## 4. CORS configuration on your host API

Your host API at `{{hostApiOrigin}}` must accept browser requests from
`{{hostPageOrigin}}`. Headers the widget sends: `Authorization`,
`Content-Type`. Action-manifest verbs: `GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE`.

Required response headers:

- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: {{hostPageOrigin}}`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Authorization, Content-Type`
{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}- `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`
{{/if}}

`/atw.init` did not detect a known framework; **REPLACE THIS** with the
CORS-configuration snippet for your stack. The standard middlewares
(Express `cors`, Fastify `@fastify/cors`, Django `corsheaders`,
Rails `rack-cors`, etc.) all accept the same origin/methods/headers
values listed above.

## 5. Run the ATW backend

The emitted `atw/.env.example` already inlines `DATABASE_URL` and
`ALLOWED_ORIGINS={{hostPageOrigin}}` from `project.md`. Paste your
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` and start the container.

**bash**

```bash
cp atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw/.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm \
  --env-file atw/.env \
  -p 4000:4000 \
  atw_backend:latest
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw\.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm `
  --env-file atw/.env `
  -p 4000:4000 `
  atw_backend:latest
```

The backend requires Postgres with the `pgvector` extension.

## 6. Static assets

Build-time-frozen frontend containers must be rebuilt before changes
take effect — copying files into a running container is a no-op.

